{{Infobox company | name = Dow Corning Corp. | logo = Dow Corning logo.jpg | type = [[Subsidiary]] | foundation = 1943 | industry = [[Manufacturing]] | location = [[Midland, Michigan]] | key_people = Mauro Gregorio, CEO & President | parent = [[DowDuPont]] | num_employees = 12,000 <ref>{{cite web | title=Five things to know about Michigan-based Dow Corning Corp. | url=http://www.mlive.com/business/mid-michigan/index.ssf/2014/11/top_5_things_to_know_about_71-.html}}</ref> | products = Speciality chemicals, silicon derived polymers | revenue = $6.12 billion (2012)<ref name = factsheet>[http://www.dowcorning.com/content/publishedlit/Global_Fast_Facts.pdf Dow Corning fast facts] (June 13, 2013)</ref> | homepage = [http://www.dowcorning.com/ www.dowcorning.com] }}
'''Dow Corning''' was<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-dowdupont-m-a/dowdupont-alters-post-merger-breakup-plans-amid-investor-pressure-idUSKCN1BN15F</ref><ref>http://www.plastverarbeiter.de/74087/dowdupont-gibt-namen-der-kuenftigen-drei-divisionen-bekannt/</ref> an American [[multinational corporation]] headquartered in [[Midland, Michigan]], United States. Originally established as a joint venture between the [[Dow Chemical Company]] and [[Corning Inc.|Corning Incorporated]], it is now owned by [[DowDuPont]] and specializes in [[silicone]] and [[silicon]]-based technology, and is the largest silicone product producer in the world.<ref name=jv/>
==History== [[File:Dow Corning, Bay City.jpg|thumb|right|Dow Corning, Bay City]] Dow Corning was formally established in 1943 as a [[joint venture]] between the American conglomerates [[Dow Chemical]] and [[Corning Glass]] to explore the potential of silicone and was a manufacturer of products for use by the U.S. military in World War II. The company began operating its first plant, in Midland, MI, in 1945. Dr. E. C. Sullivan was named president, and Dr. William R. Collings was named general manager in 1943. Dr. Collings later became president from 1954 until 1962.<ref name=timeline /> It expanded into Canada and Europe in 1948, and into South America and Japan in 1961.<ref name= 'timeline'>{{cite news|title=Michigan-based Dow Corning: Timeline of a global success story|url=http://www.mlive.com/business/mid-michigan/index.ssf/2014/11/dow_corning_timeline.html|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>
A large, majority-owned subsidiary of Dow Corning Corporation is the [[Hemlock Semiconductor Corporation]].<ref name=jv>{{cite news |author=Robert Westervelt |coauthors= |title=Dow Corning |url=http://www.chemweek.com/dowcorning2011/ |quote=Dow Corning, a 50–50 jv between Dow Chemical and Corning, is the world’s largest silicones producer and has a controlling 62.5% stake in Hemlock Semiconductor (Hemlock, MI), the world’s leading producer of polysilicon used in semiconductor and solar wafer production. ... |newspaper=[[Chemical Week]] |date=June 24, 2011 |accessdate=2015-02-10 }}</ref> It is one of the world's largest producers of high-purity polycrystalline silicon, which is sold in varying purity grades for use in both [[semiconductor]] [[Wafer (electronics)|silicon wafer]] manufacture and [[photovoltaics]] applications as solar cells.<ref name=timeline />
In 2002, the company created the Xiameter brand as an online-only distributor. As of 2011, Xiameter offers 2,100 of Dow Corning’s 7,000 products.
On November 13, 2014, Dow Chemical's CEO [[Andrew N. Liveris]] revealed in a presentation to investors that Corning Incorporated intended to exit the joint venture of 71 years, citing other priorities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dow Says Corning Wants to Exit 71-Year-Old Venture|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-13/dow-says-corning-wants-to-exit-71-year-old-venture.html|accessdate=16 November 2014|work=Bloomberg News|publisher=Bloomberg|first=Jack|last=Kaskey|date=13 November 2014}}</ref> Following the December 11, 2015 announcement that it would merge with [[DuPont]], Dow also announced that it had reached a deal to acquire Corning's stake in Dow Corning in exchange for $4.8 billion in cash and Corning gaining a roughly 40% stake in Hemlock Semiconductor Corporation. Dow Chemical assumed full ownership of Dow Corning on June 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Corning to Swap Stake In Dow Corning For $4.8 Billion, Semiconductor Stake|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/corning-to-sell-stake-in-dow-corning-venture-for-4-8-billion-1449846313|accessdate=11 December 2015|agency=wsj.com|publisher=wsj.com|date=11 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg-dowdemerge>{{cite news|title=Dow Chemical to Take Full Control of Dow Corning Venture|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-11/dow-chemical-takes-100-percent-stake-in-dow-corning-venture|accessdate=16 December 2015|work=Bloomberg News|agency=Bloomberg}}</ref>
==Products== Dow Corning markets over 7000 products include various sealants, adhesives, rubbers, lubricants, silicon oils and solvents. Around 2,100 of these are available through the Dow Corning online-only distributor Xiameter, including fluids, gels, resins. The range of industries targeted by Dow Corning products spans from electronics and automotive to construction, healthcare and others. In recent years, the company has expanded production of solar cells, particularly through its majority stake in [[Hemlock Semiconductor Corporation|Hemlock]], which accounts for a polysilicon franchise worth over $1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dow Corning: Solar, Sustainability Drive Turnaround|url=http://www.chemweek.com/dowcorning2011/|website=IHS Chemical Week Magazine|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> In 2011, then-CTO Gregg Zank explained that the company tries to focus its product development on societal “megatrends” (e.g. energy scarcity and urbanization).<ref>{{cite web|title=Innovation in chemicals: An interview with Dow Corning’s CEO and CTO|url=http://www.mckinsey.com/insights/energy_resources_materials/innovation_in_chemicals_an_interview_with_dow_cornings_ceo_and_cto|website=McKinsey’s & Company|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref>
==Problems with breast implants== Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, [[class action|class-action]] lawsuits<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/24bn-breastimplant-offer-1247358.html independent.co.uk – $2.4bn breast-implant offer], 1997-08-26</ref> claimed that Dow Corning's silicone [[breast implant]]s caused systemic health problems. The claims first centered on [[breast cancer]] and then migrated to a range of [[autoimmunity|autoimmune disease]]s, including [[Systemic lupus erythematosus|lupus]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and various neurological problems. This led to numerous lawsuits beginning in 1984 and culminating in a 1998 multibillion-dollar class action settlement.<ref name = frontline>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/implants/cron.html Chronology of silicone breast implants]. ''Frontline''</ref> As a result, Dow Corning was in [[bankruptcy]] protection for nine years, ending in June 2004<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1021/cen-v082n015.p005| title = Out of the Woods| journal = Chemical & Engineering News| volume = 82| issue = 15| pages = 5| year = 2004| last1 = Reisch | first1 = M. }}</ref> during which time it largely withdrew from clinical markets.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1021/cen-v071n002.p013| title = Dow Corning Moving Back on Track Following Breast Implant Controversy| journal = Chemical & Engineering News| volume = 71| issue = 2| pages = 13| year = 1993| last1 = Reisch | first1 = M. S. }}</ref>
Although a number of independent reviews, including the [[National Academy of Medicine|Institute of Medicine]] in the United States, subsequently indicated that silicone breast implants do not cause breast cancers or any identifiable systemic diseases,<ref name = nyt>{{cite news |author=[[Gina Kolata]] |coauthors= |title=Panel Confirms No Major Illness Tied to Implants |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9B03E6D9103BF932A15755C0A96F958260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fOrganizations%2fI%2fInstitute%20of%20Medicine |quote=An independent panel of 13 scientists convened by the Institute of Medicine at the request of Congress has concluded that silicone breast implants do not cause any major diseases. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 21, 1999 |accessdate=2015-02-10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Colas | first = André | authorlink = |author2=Curtis, Jim | year = 2004 | title = Biomaterials Science, Second Edition: An Introduction to Materials in Medicine | url = http://www.dowcorning.com/content/publishedlit/52-1069-01.pdf | publisher = Elsevier, Academic Press | location = | isbn = 978-0-12-582463-7 }}</ref> on 21 March 2017, the [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] issued a statement indicating that women with breast implants have a "very low but increased risk"<ref name="breastcancer.org">{{Cite web|url=https://www.breastcancer.org/research-news/fda-updates-on-textured-implants-and-cancer|title=FDA Updates Warning on Link Between Textured Breast Implants and Rare Cancer|date=22 March 2017|website=BreastCancer.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119020102/https://www.breastcancer.org/research-news/fda-updates-on-textured-implants-and-cancer|archive-date=19 Jan 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=15 Aug 2018}}</ref> of getting a rare form of cancer called [[anaplastic large-cell lymphoma]] (ALCL).<ref name="breastcancer.org"/> The cancer is associated with nine deaths, the FDA said.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/21/health/breast-implants-cancer-deaths.html|title=9 Deaths Are Linked to Rare Cancer From Breast Implants|last=Grady|first=Denise|date=21 March 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=15 Aug 2018}}</ref> These findings have caused an uptick in breast implant removal surgeries.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}
