{{Infobox person | name = Gilbert Bigio | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = 1935[[Circa|c.]] <!-- Webster University (Miami Herald) mentions on 3/21/04 (3 mo. and 3 weeks into the year) that Bigio was 68. It is most likely his birth was 1935, opposed to 1936 --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | nationality = Haitian | other_names = | occupation = Founder of [[GB Group]] | years_active = | known_for = Wealthiest person in Haiti | notable_works = }}
'''Gilbert Bigio''' is a [[Haiti]]an billionaire and retired businessman. He is the founder of [[GB Group]] and the wealthiest person in Haiti. He is also the de facto leader of Haiti's [[History of the Jews in Haiti|Jewish community]] and an honorary consul to [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.webster.edu/~corbetre/haiti/misctopic/ethnic/jewshistory2.htm |title=Haiti's Few Jews Hold On To History |publisher=[[Webster University]] |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/international/scenes_haiti_relief_mission |title=Scenes From The Haiti Relief Mission |publisher=''[[The Jewish Week]]'' |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/haiti.html |title=Haiti |publisher=[[Jewish Virtual Library]] |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>
==Early years== Bigio is from a [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic]] Jewish family from [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]], whose family emigrated to Haiti in 1896. Ever since, the family has been involved in commercial activities all throughout the country. The Bigio family has remained in Haiti, prominent in business affairs for three generations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2mJB8hZzjxIC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=Cavaly+haiti+football&source=bl&ots=Q5w1Lqr47J&sig=ShLRSBRfBjbz4nZ3FVLSBE2Ys-Q&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Sj_QVJaNIo7IsATerYDYDg&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=Cavaly%20haiti%20football&f=false |title=Historical Dictionary of Haiti |author=Hall, Michael R. |page=120 |year=2012 |isbn=9780810875494 |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2004/02/13/archive/around-the-jewish-world-as-haiti-burns-its-few-jews-choose-business-over-politics |title=Around the Jewish World As Haiti Burns, Its Few Jews Choose Business over Politics |editor=Press |date=13 February 2004 |publisher=JTA (Jewish Telegraphic Agency) |accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/41099/two-haitian-jews-working-with-idf-to-help-survivors/ |title=Two Haitian Jews working with IDF to help survivors |editor=Solomont, E.B. |date=21 January 2010 |publisher=JWeekly |accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref>
