{{Notability|biographies|date=November 2008}}
'''Teun Draaisma''' is the European equity strategist at [[Morgan Stanley]].<ref name="investing.businessweek.com">{{cite web|author=Teun Draaisma |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/businessweek/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=8308024&symbol=MS |title=Teun Draaisma: Executive Profile & Biography - Businessweek |publisher=Investing.businessweek.com |date=2003-09-16 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> He was noticed when he warned investors to sell equities in June 2007, just before the [[credit crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sakoui |first=Anousha |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5e5479a2-aa11-11dd-958b-000077b07658.html |title=Morgan Stanley strategist points to buy signal |publisher=FT.com |date=2008-11-04 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>

On 3 November 2008, he  said that severe part of the bear market is over, even though many short-term risks exist.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher |first=Nick |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/marketforceslive/2008/nov/04/marketturmoil-morganstanley |title=Morgan Stanley calls an end to bear market &#124; Business |publisher=theguardian.com |date=2008-11-04 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> He "said that stocks were now flashing a 'full house' buy signal after markets have priced in an earnings [[recession]], and retail investors, purchasing managers and sell-side analysts have all capitulated."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minyanville.com/articles/Fed-gm-economy-F-payroll-ISM/index/a/19918 |title=Prieur's Perspective: Welcome To Wall Street, President Obama &#124; Business News &#124; Minyanville's Wall Street |publisher=Minyanville.com |date=2008-11-10 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>

